    <body><div type="letter">
      <p>[a few characters on the far right of the heading are cut off, what's visible is transcribed] St. James' Sqr 5 o'clock. Satur 30th April</p>
      <p>Keep the enclosed.</p>
      <p>My Dearest William. I forgot yesterday to name two things to you-- first, that Tubbs is sure no ammunition returned to Ockham-- secondly, that yesterday morning Captain Henry called just as we were going to set out for the Panorama. He sent up his name to me, with a little parcel of choice Eau De Cologne he had just</p>
      <p>got from somewhere, and a most polite note begging my acceptance of the same. As I had no inclination either to be detained two hours at home, or to have him for an escort to the Panorama, I was rude enough to send word that I was engaged &amp; could not have the pleasure of seeing him till some other occasion, but was very much obliged for the parcel.</p>
      <p>I wonder why Emily has written to you. Your mother had heard nothing of</p>
      <p>her intended movements, till Hester told her today. It appears that your uncle Tom Grenville (who by the bye called here yesterday, but when I was out) has made Emily a present lately of a sum of money-- with good intention no doubt, but little judgment.-- If Emily calls with Lady G. Fain I am determined not to see the latter, and if the worst comes to the worst, I shall send down word I am engaged, but hope to see Miss Emily King some other time.</p>
      <p>I allow this is a strong measure, but I think you would approve of it.--</p>
      <p>Tomorrow I shall have no letter from ou, which I shall not like. Your letters quite enlliven the little Bird.-- Both Hester &amp; I have slight colds in our heads, but of no consequence. I want to have taken her to the Diorama today, but have not on this account. I have been with Lady G. Murray this afternoon, and she has engaged me to be one of the Patronesses to the ball that is to be given for the benefit of the Children's Friend Society. Perhaps</p>
      <p>I ought not to have consented without asking your leave, &amp; if you disapprove of it, I can easily withdraw still. I suppose there are about 2 dozen other names down also-- Duchess of Kent at the head.-- They want you to go to the ball as well as the dinner.-- Charlotte comes here this evening.</p>
      <p>Even I feel this cold weather, &amp; I have no warm mate at night, neither has he a warm bird.--</p>
      <p>Yours most affecly A. A. K.</p>
      <p>I did like Madme Tricoupe very much, &amp; I think her still beautiful. You &amp; I will call together there, if I am still well when you return.</p>
      <p>[folio 45 is blank]</p>
    </div></body>
